tion of metempsychotic selfhood into an expressly poetic event. His vision of transmigration viscerally celebrates the poet's ability to assume and live in other bodies; his American poet seeks to incorporate the entire nation into his own person so that he can speak for every man and woman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aSelf-consciousness (Awareness) in literature. 0aTransmigration in literature. 4aAmerican Literature. 4aEsotericism. 4aHinduism. 4aHistory of Science. 4aIdealism. 4aIdentity. 4aMysticism. 4aNeoplatonism. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPlatonism. 4aReligion. 4aRomanticism. 4aTranscendentalism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823242375zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823242375423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823242375.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK